	(text "Phase-flip per-channel switch.\n\nOptional.\n\nI personally didn’t need\nit for my build (I have\nthis option on my\npedalboard). But it’s\nvery easy to add since\nthere is an input\ntransformer."
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 22.352 101.092 0)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 1.27 1.27)
			)
			(justify left top)
		)
		(uuid "0c9e9bae-e9fd-47df-9a3c-3c7645e624b0")
	)
	(text "DC power source RC filter.\n\nCut-off frequency is ≈8Hz.\n\nProvides you with clean power.\nAlso the resistors can provide\na touch of sag at fast transients."
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 98.298 105.918 0)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 1.27 1.27)
			)
			(justify left top)
		)
		(uuid "7b100d03-cf54-43be-b6db-909bcc877899")
	)
	(text "The input transformers (T1 and T2) play 2 roles:\n\n1. Balance the input signal in case it is unbalanced while\n   supporting balanced input signals too\n\n2. Amplify-ish the signal (2x times, 1:2) to compensate the\n   gain loss on the DF reduction resistors (the feature can\n   be turned off by moving the LEVEL switch to 1:1 position)\n\nThe LEVEL switch allows to configure the transformer to\neither 1:1 ratio (series windings, 6 and 7 are tired together),\nor to 1:2 ratio (parallel windings, 5 is tied to 6,\nand 7 is tied to 8)."
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 148.082 136.906 0)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 1.27 1.27)
			)
			(justify left top)
		)
		(uuid "9dd36f15-7433-4ebb-82b1-a22faa24dc65")
	)
	(text "Damping factor reduction\noutput ballast resistors.\n\nEach side of the bridge-mode\namp “sees” half of the load.\nSo for 8Ω load it “sees” 4Ω.\nThe ballast DF resistor\nis 6Ω for each side.\nThe damping factor formula is\nload divided by output impedance\nof the the amplifier (ballast\nresistors dominate here).\n4Ω load / 6Ω ballast ≈ 0.66 DF\n1 DF or less is similar to a\ntube guitar power amplifier.\n\nResistors are installed\non a heatsink. I install\n4x of 100W 6Ω on a single\nheatsink. So one heatsink\nfor both 2 channels.\n\nIt gets pretty warm at proper\nvolumes but not too hot to\nworry about active cooling.\nThough if you gonna really\nblast stadium volumes or push\ntoo much low frequencies active\ncooling is recommended."
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 213.868 97.282 0)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 1.27 1.27)
			)
			(justify left top)
		)
		(uuid "a9cdf701-54b5-4d15-8615-12070402b9e7")
	)
	(text "Output capacitors bleeder\nresistors.\n\nWhen hot-plugging/unplugging\nspeaker cables capacitors\ncan get a charge spike that\nwould block the potentials\nfrom resolving. Thus blocking\nthe amplifier from working\nproperly until the capacitors\nslowly discharge.\n\nThese resistors allow to bleed\nany parasitic charge to ground\nrelatively quickly preventing\nthe amplifier from locking."
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 271.526 92.964 0)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 1.27 1.27)
			)
			(justify left top)
		)
		(uuid "e2e4453f-cc88-4cbb-8a18-1fbb9442f6da")
	)
